ony in Greek Culture -- tHuman-animal Sex in Ancient Greece -- tThe Womb Inside the Male Member: A Lucianic Twist -- tPart V: Sex and Disgust -- tSex and Disgust in Martial’s Epigrams -- tPart VI: The Scripts of Sexuality: Drama, Novel, Papyri and Later Texts -- tTo Voice the Physical: Sex and the Soil in Aeschylus -- tSeminal Figures: Aristophanes and the Tradition of Sexual Imagery -- tThe Maiden who Knew Nothing about Sex: A Scabrous Theme in Novella and Comedy -- tSex and Abuse in Unhappy Marriages in Late Antique Oxyrhynchus: The Case of Two Women’s Narratives Preserved on Papyrus -- t“Asexuality” in the Greek Papyrus Letters -- tFrom Plato’s Symposium to Methodius’ and Late Antique Hagiography: “Female” Readings of Male Sexuality -- tNotes on Editors and Contributors -- tIndex Locorum -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume aims to revisit, further explore and tease out the textual, but also non-textual sources in an attempt to reconstruct a clearer picture of a particular aspect of sexuality, i.e. sexual practices, in Greco-Roman antiquity. Sexual practices refers to a part of the overarching notion of sexuality: specifically, the acts of sexual intercourse, the erogenous capacities and genital functions of male and female body, and any other physical or biological actions that define one’s sexual identity or orientation. This volume aims to approach not simply the acts of sexual intercourse themselves, but also their legal, social, political, religious, medical, cultural/moral and interdisciplinary (e.g. emotional, performative) perspectives, as manifested in a range of both textual and non-textual evidence (i.e. architecture, iconography, epigraphy, etc.). The insights taken from the contributions to this volume would enable researchers across a range of disciplines – e.g. sex/gender studies, comparative literature, psychology and cognitive neuroscience – to use theoretical perspectives, methodologies and conceptual tools to frame the sprawling examination of aspects of sexuality in broad terms, or sexual practices in particular.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aAntike / Anthropologie. 4aGeschlecht. 4aSex. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aSexual practices.  abody.  afemale.  amale.1 aBednarek, Bartłomiej, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemetriou, Kyriakos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemetriou, Kyriakos, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEfthymiadis, Stephanos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvangelou, Gabriel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFountoulakis, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatzilambrou, Rosalia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHubbard, Thomas K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHöschele, Regina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKanellakis, Dimitrios, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapparis, Konstantinos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKazantzidis, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKazantzidis, George, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKonstantakos, Ioannis M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoroli, Aikaterini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalheiro Magalhães, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManousakis, Nik